🏆 The "Login Feedback" Challenge
Scenario: You are building a login page. You have an <input type="text"> and a <h1> that acts as a status message.

The Goal:

When the user presses a key inside the input field, check the length (how many characters) of the text they typed.

If the text has more than 8 characters:

Change the <h1> text to say: "Strong Password".

Change the <h1> color to green.

Add a class to the <h1> called "success".

If the text has 8 characters or less:

Change the <h1> text to say: "Too Short".

Change the <h1> color to red.

Check if the <h1> has the class "success". If it does, remove it.

🛠️ Tools you will need (New stuff to research):
.val(): This is how jQuery gets the text inside an input.

.length: You used this with arrays; it works on strings too!

.keypress() or .on("input", ...): To detect when the user types.

.text("New Message"): To change the text inside an element.